Zig generics use no special template syntax. A generic data structure is an ordinary function that takes a type parameter at compile time and returns a struct type:

```zig
fn List(comptime T: type) type {
    return struct {
        items: []T,
        // ...
    };
}
```

Here `List` is a regular function that runs at compile time, takes a type, and returns a type. Calling `List(u32)` produces a new struct type — the same machinery as generic specialisation in C++ or Rust, but expressed without special syntax. Conditional compilation falls out the same way: `comptime if (target == .windows)` is just an `if` evaluated at compile time, and the not-taken branch never reaches codegen.
